metadata.name: Incomplete Convergence #249
metadata.description:
Cutting an optimization process short can lead to interesting results. This series builds on the earlier Sneronoi series but doesn't attempt to run to full convergence. Images are generated by gradient descent and the optimization process is shown as an animation. Each piece is considered final when the animation stops.

There are ten different color palettes, each with four different options for background colors. There are also different shapes drawn in the background and different modes in which the foreground and the background are blended together. In combination, these options result in a wide range of distinct visual outputs. Made with D3.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png (4000x4000).

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art

metadata.name: Before/After #135
metadata.description:
A visual representation of a non-linear transformation. Each line connects a data point before the transformation has been applied to its corresponding point after the transformation has been applied. Switch to debug mode to see the untransformed and transformed points. Outline mode shows only the lines and can be used for plotting. (Plotting will likely work best on outputs where the total number of lines is low.)

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript, with the compute-intensive transformation (t-SNE) implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. The final artwork is a static SVG file that can be downloaded and displayed at any resolution. No external libraries have been used.

More information about this collection is provided here: https://clauswilke.com/art/project/before-after

I would like to thank Bartholomew Littlesilver for helpful artistic feedback, Liam Egan for help with creating plottable SVGs, and BRUTALISTI and neophob for encouraging me to pursue AssemblyScript for implementing performance-critical code.

Press 'm' to cycle between normal, debug, and outline mode.

Press 's' to save as svg.

Press 'p' to save as png.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #398
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Noodles #236
metadata.description:
The technical prophylaxis the brain performs from time to time is like a cruel joke. Because it does not warn us about what it is going to do and how we are going to feel about it.
There are times when we can't get our heads together. You know, there's a little confusion in the mind. I used to think of it as a mess of threads, tangled together and tied in knots that can't be untangled. It was a very naïve notion. I think the tangle of the mind is more like a noodle. Sticky, heavy, drawn-out and tasteless. Cold or hot, I don't know, but I don't like either. And the thoughts and images trapped in this mass certainly lend some flavor, though I'm not sure if that's good or bad. In the end, they just keep coming up over and over in your head, alternating and bringing nothing new to the table. It looks as if they are signaling you something and don't want to leave you alone, but they are just stuck in a noodle, just like you are.

metadata.name: MetaRack #78
metadata.description:
MetaRack is a generative modular synthesizer capable of producing random yet nice sounding patches. MetaRack is written from scratch, with pure sample-by-sample processing and no 3rd party libraries were used for audio handling. Also no samples or prepared audio files were used in this project, everything you hear is generated on-the-fly. The only library involved in MetaRack is p5js which is used for drawing graphical elements.

MetaRack is also a part of a bigger project - we are working on a gallery based on fxhash ecosystem which will allow collectors to connect and arrange their tokens, probably producing derivative NFTs. When launched, MetaRack token holders will receive an exclusive module collection. For more info please read the article https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/metarack-modular-synthesizer

Interface:
S - save
L - load
SHIFT - change modulation depth while rotating a knob

@ferluht
@alexexeev
2022

metadata.name: just one long day #37
metadata.description: It's just a very long day. 365 revolutions around the sun, 8,760 hours and thousands of unfamiliar eyes waiting for the next morning. What does it mean to be stuck in one day? When everything around you is changing, living, breathing, dying, only you alone, like a stone statue. Nothing can touch you, and your feelings are externally muted to a minimum. Calm, joy, fear, anxiety, despair. You don't seem to have lost the ability to live, but you are somehow helpless and immobile. All your thoughts and experiences flow through your empty body, driving you insane. Everything around you distorts and changes in your eyes. And all you can do is remind yourself that it's just one long day. And I hope your tomorrow comes very soon.

metadata.name: Face of Death #8
metadata.description:
If we talk about Death as a guide to eternity, it is impossible not to mention its many faces. What does Death look like? Every culture has its own answer to this question. In the Bible, death represents an angel sent by God and endowed with great power. Norse mythology gave Death the name Hel. In ancient Greece, her work was done by Thanatos, Charon, Moros. I very much understand the human desire to personify that which frightens us with its obscurity. 
In studying how people of different cultures view the end of life, I have come to my own conclusions. I do not believe that ideas about the faces of Death are limited to culture, philosophy and religion. I think that for every Soul Death takes on a new face and this is not by accident. The face of Death is a projection of how one has treated one's life and in particular its last seconds.


Code by PureSpider
